  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This study provides insights into a brainstem circuit that regulates cough-like airway defensive behaviors in mice, contributing to our understanding of respiratory reflexes and potential therapeutic targets.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research titled \"A brainstem circuit controls cough-like airway defensive behaviors in mice,\" published as a preprint in 2024, explores the neural mechanisms underlying cough reflexes in murine models. This work, involving collaboration among researchers from distinguished institutions such as ShanghaiTech University, Guangzhou Medical University, and Huazhong University of Science and Technology, illuminates crucial pathways that may inform future studies on respiratory health and disease.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the work currently has a single citation on OpenAlex, its early sharing as a preprint indicates that it is influencing cutting-edge discourse within the field. The preprint has already secured one citation, illustrating its potential impact on ongoing research in respiratory reflex mechanisms. Furthermore, the preprint status emphasizes the authors' commitment to open science, which fosters early engagement and feedback from the scientific community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of funding agencies listed does not detract from the significance of the institutional support behind this research. The collaboration among varied universities highlights a concerted effort to tackle complex questions within neuroscience, specifically concerning cough regulation. This collective expertise strengthens the reliability of the findings and suggests that the research is positioned to attract further exploration and validation in subsequent studies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the metrics reveal that there are no substantial community engagements on platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, the foundational nature of this preprint establishes a groundwork for future discourse. The implications of this research may resonate beyond the academic sphere, especially as studies focusing on airway defense mechanisms gain more attention in health-related contexts. Continued attention to its milestones, including any potential downstream research that leverages these findings, could expand the conversation within the scientific community.</p>",
